2. Related Work
2.1 Low-Rank Adaptations

LoRA (Hu et al., 2021) parameterizes weight updates as $W = W_0 + BA$ where $B$ and $A$ are low-rank. Our work extends this to continuous time: $W(t) = W_0 + \sum \alpha_i(t) U_i V_i^T$.
2.2 Hypernetworks

Hypernetworks (Ha et al., 2016) generate weights as a function of an embedding. Temporal manifolds can be seen as hypernetworks where the embedding is time $t$, but with explicit low-rank structure.
2.3 Mode Connectivity

Mode connectivity (Garipov et al., 2018; Draxler et al., 2018) shows that different minima can be connected by low-loss paths. Our work actively learns such paths for task interpolation.
2.4 Neural ODEs

Neural ODEs (Chen et al., 2018) model continuous dynamics of activations. Temporal manifolds apply the same philosophy to weights rather than activations.
2.5 Multi-Task Learning

Traditional multi-task learning uses shared backbones with task-specific heads (Caruana, 1997). Temporal manifolds offer an alternative: a continuous spectrum of tasks.
3. Temporal Manifolds: Formulation and Properties
3.1 Mathematical Formulation

A temporal manifold layer is defined as:

W(t)=W0+1r‚ąĎi=1kőĪi(t)UiViTW(t)=W0‚Äč+r1‚Äč‚ąĎi=1k‚ÄčőĪi‚Äč(t)Ui‚ÄčViT‚Äč

Where:

    $r$ is the rank (scaling factor from LoRA)

    $k$ is the number of basis directions

    $\alpha_i(t)$ is a learnable function of time

For a multi-layer network, each layer has its own set of basis matrices ${U_i^{(l)}, V_i^{(l)}}$ and its own $\alpha_i^{(l)}(t)$, but they share the same time $t$.
3.2 Properties

Continuity: For continuous $\alpha_i(t)$, $W(t)$ is continuous, ensuring smooth transitions.

Efficiency: Additional parameters scale as $O(k \cdot \text{rank} \cdot (\text{in} + \text{out}))$, independent of the number of tasks.

Geometric interpretation: The set ${W(t) : t \in [0,1]}$ is a 1D curve in weight space. With multiple latent dimensions, it becomes a manifold.
3.3 Training Procedure

We use a two-phase training protocol:

Phase 1: Pure tasks (epochs 1-20)

    Train only on $t=0$ and $t=1$ with hard labels

    Alternates between the two tasks each epoch

    Goal: Establish clean task representations

Phase 2: Interpolation (epochs 21-50)

    Gradually introduce intermediate $t$ values

    Curriculum: start near anchors, expand to full range

    Loss: MSE on blended targets $(1-t)y_A + t y_B$

